The paper presents a model-based deep reinforcement learning approach for robotic crowd navigation, which involves reasoning about the relations between all agents based on their latent features and using a Graph Convolutional Network to encode higher-order interactions in each agent's state representation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the use of deep learning techniques such as Graph Convolutional Networks and value estimation suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. Finally, the focus on multi-step lookahead planning and temporal evolution of human crowds suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
